O God! Thou art my God alone;  
When silence weaves the night’s dark veil,  
And all the world seems turned to stone,  
In secret corners where I fail.  

I seek Thy face, I call Thy name,  
My soul, like parched earth, thirsts for Thee;  
No fleeting idol’s empty claim  
Can fill the longing deep in me.  

Thou art my dawn, my guiding star,  
The flame that warms my trembling heart;  
Though distant lands and shadows mar,  
Thy steadfast love will not depart.  

O God! Alone, my refuge be;  
Within Thy arms, I rest and sing;  
My hope, my strength, my liberty—  
O God, my God, my everything.

In the blood-red dusk of Ilium, the rage of gods unfurls—
Patroclus dons Achilles’ mail, and fate’s wheel slowly whirls.
The ships are ringed with fire and doom, the Greeks pressed to their knees;
The Trojans surge, the ocean roars, the wind laments with pleas.

Patroclus, lion-hearted, drives the foe before his spear;
Hector waits, Apollo lurks, and death draws ever near.
The armor gleams, the chariots race, the dust becomes a shroud;
A friend falls, a hero weeps, beneath the thunder loud.

Achilles’ wrath, once banked in grief, ignites a storm anew;
His mother brings him shining arms, the world in bronze and blue.
Rivers rage and Xanthus chokes, the gods themselves contend;
The cost of pride, the price of war—no mortal can amend.

So sing, O Muse, of Ilium’s pain, of friendship, wrath, and woe;
Of fates entwined, of valor’s end, where ancient legends grow.
